y Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaufort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of English (originally French)   Beaufort  . It is found mainly among African Americans. Compare   Bluford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bluford","meanings":["Possibly also English: habitational name from a lost or unidentified place. The name occurs in records of the 19th century but is now extinct in the British Isles.","Variant of   Blueford  , a surname of English (ultimately French) origin. It is found mainly among African Americans."]}]},{"name":"Pierre","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From New Testament Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Pierre Rogier de Beaufort was born about 1241, in Rosiers-d'Égletons, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France as the son of Pierre Rogier de Beaufort. He married Nadale de Maulmont in 1263, in Rosiers-d'Égletons, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1300, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"environ 1241–1300":"umbes 1241–1300","1241–1300":"1241–1300","1245–1301":"1245–1301","1264–1324":"1264–1324","1265–1338":"1265–1338","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1272–1347":"1272–1347","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","environ 1241":"umbes 1241","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1241":"1241","1272":"1272","1338":"1338","1347":"1347","1324":"1324","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","8 janvier 1265":"8. jaanuar 1265","Rosiers-d'Égletons, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Rosiers-d'Égletons, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Rosiers-d'Égletons, Ussel, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Rosiers-d'Égletons, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1241–1300":"noin 1241–1300","1241–1300":"1241–1300","1245–1301":"1245–1301","1264–1324":"1